1. So it was no coincidence that you came to the Library, Roland.
2. I see. You helped me attain my freedom, but it wasn’t for my sake…
3. You just used me like a tool.
4. Did you get the result you wanted?
5. Why didn’t you try to stop me or kill me right away, then?
6. …
7. Then… Who will pay for the misery I went through?
8. There was nothing else I could do; all I knew was to make them suffer the same pain…
9. …
10. …Seeing you shed tears is an unfamiliar sight.
11. …I only want to be compensated for my suffering.
12. At least I used a method that isn’t forcef—
13. …
14. ……
15. This is the end of the line, Roland. I suppose this is another sorrow I must overcome.
16. …
17. Thank you so much. I’ll move onwards to the next stage of my life.
18. It’s time you accepted your fate and returned to books.
19. You know better than anyone else that it’s pointless to oppose me in the Library, don’t you?
20. Maybe this is what I should have done sooner.
21. It was silly of me to make a deal with you…
22. I wouldn’t have to feel this heartache, had I not made the offer that day and lived by myself.
23. You tried to interrupt me, so I did what I had to do.
24. After all, you chose to stand against me with the flesh and freedom you’ve gained.
25. You could’ve walked away and disappeared from my sight, and I wouldn’t have harmed you.
26. …That’s how fickle the human mind can be. Wouldn’t you agree?
27. I want this to be your final and permanent slumber.
28. …Good work.
29. How many colleagues of yours… the so-called ‘Bookhunters’ have you killed?
30. And countless more people will die in the future.
31. I know humans. I learned the secrets of mankind that the City had been hiding from them.
32. Thank you for putting me to rest, o child who had no name.
33. …Roland, I’m going to let go. Someone has to break this cycle, ultimately…
34. After all, even I couldn’t escape the treadwheel turning for this City.
35. And if I have to be entrapped in more of such cycles, perpetrating deeds similar to what I’ve done… I…
36. I don’t think I could live that life further…
37. I would continue to be crushed under the everturning wheel; the only difference would be how harshly it smothers me…
38. Achieving freedom was meaningless in a world like this.
39. I… feel their weight now, and it’s too much for me to bear… I thought this would be the last time.
40. I sincerely mean it… If I shut my eyes again and shed blood one last time… I thought I would be free to live as I want.
41. Alas, I could never be truly free as long as I was chained to the bonds of the City.
42. You, I, and this Library are soaked in the blood of many.
43. All the actions I took in pursuit of freedom only sped the treadwheel.
44. I convinced myself that it was an inevitable sacrifice I had to put up with, for the sake of my freedom and amends for my agony…
45. And once this was over… I wanted to stop taking precious things from anyone.
46. I know what loss and pain are, how they feel…
47. However, the wheel that is this City is powered by those, crushing everything in its path.
48. If I have to snuff out what belongs to me with my own hand in the end…
49. And if life requires me to spill the blood of others, or lets my own blood so that I may live on…
50. I’d much rather remove my grip on this goal…
51. At the very least, I refuse to die under the wheel.
52. The books, the librarians, the Library… and finally, my own freedom.
53. I’ll let go of them all first.
54. I will no longer cling to them. I won’t try to keep them in my clutch anymore.
55. If I give it all up… then I can reverse this…
56. At least, those who died in the Library can be brought back.
57. Yes… I made this decision by dint of my own will entirely.
58. This will be the first wish and the last choice I make… since I’ve become free from all restraints for the first time.
59. Let me ask you one last favor.
60. I am going to leave myself vulnerable for a short while.
61. Expelling everything I’ve absorbed until now won’t be a simple feat.
62. Could you leave me be while I do that?
63. I’m asking you as a dear friend.
64. …If you still consider me a friend, that is.
65. I won’t stop you, but don’t worry.
66. When I’m done, everything will go back to the way it was; I’ll disappear without a trace.
67. …There isn’t much time, so I’ll get started right away.
